ce:section.ce:para:
For evaluation of prepared carbon dots capability for ferric ions determination in a typical real sample, the unknown concentration of ferric ions in the human blood serum sample was estimated by the standard addition method. In this assay, the various volumes of FeCl3 standard solution (1 mM) (including 50, 150, 350, 500, 750, 1000, 1500, and 2500 μL) were added in a series of 5 mL of volumetric flask (except for the first volumetric flask) containing N/B co-doped CDs (0.1 mg/mL). After adding EDTA (0.5 M) to this mixed solution, Tris-buffer (pH 5, 0.05 M) and KCl (0.2 M) were added to all of the volumetric flasks, too. Then, a portion (200 µL) of a human serum sample was directly added to all of them, without protein removal process, unlike most previous studies. Then, all of the mixed solutions were diluted up to 5 mL using ultrapure water before incubation step to ensure the concentration of ferric ions in the linear range. Indeed, the real serum sample with and without ferric ions spike was directly treated with N/B co-doped CDs in the presence of known concentrations of EDTA, Tris buffer, and KCl. In these conditions, iron ions are released from transferrin protein. Details of the release mechanism have been mentioned in previous reports [45,68]. After shaking of mixed solutions for ∼ 15 min, fluorescence intensity at λex = 360 nm was recorded. To determine the amount of Fe3+ in the blood serum sample by standard addition method, the net changes of fluorescence intensity (ΔF = F0 – F) as an obtained response, was plotted versus volume of the added standard iron solutions (Fig. 6
                        ). After iron releasing from transferrin, it requires a suitable iron sequestering agent to trap released iron (such as pyrophosphate [71], or N/B co-doped CDs at the present work) and prevent iron rebinding to transferrin. Based on Fig. 6, the fluorescence quenching intensity (F0 – F) as a response signal, has a linear relationship (with R2 = 0.9903) versus the added volumes of Fe3+ standard solution. The equation was achieved as: (F0 – F) = 9756.8 [Fe3+] + 3831.2. The obtained results of all assays (repeated three times, n = 3) were expressed as mean concentration of ferric ions and relative standard deviation (RSD) including uncertainty of measurements in a serum sample was found to be 1.090 mg L–1 (RSD = 0.459%), by calibration curve method and 1.087 mg L–1 (RSD = 0.386%), by standard addition plot, which were well consistent with obtained results of AAS reference method (1.077 mg L–1, RSD = 0.597%), which can be seen in the Fig. S9, and medical laboratory response (1.120 mg L–1, RSD = 6.43%) by a commertial instrument (Biotecnica, BT 3000), as a routine analyzer. To perform the reproducibility and reproducibility test, each measurement was performed with three replicates at different times. The obtained results from three assay methods, were listed in Table 1
                        .
